The proton beam and irradiation times used were-
20 Nanoamperes and 3-5 hour for Pb foils,
36 Nanoamperes and 1 hour for Nai pellets,
20 Nanoamperes and 3 hour for RbCl pellets.
The  stacks  were  repeatedly measured over a
period of several day.
total error includes:
The Error in the primary incident energy of the
proton beam.
The error in the total number of protons on the
targets (mainly due to the error of the monitor
reactions) in the stack.
The statistical error in the integrated
area of the photo-peaks.
The error in the counting statistics.
The error in the absolute efficiency of the
germanium detector.
The error in the attenuation corrections.
The error in the decay-data.
The Error in the counting geometry.
The error of irradiation and decay times.

x4freetext: /by Authors/.The purity of I-123 produced by the
I-127(p,5n)Xe-123-I-123 reaction is determined by the
proton energy and the target thickness.
The Na-I pellets of thickness varying from 0.45 to
0.55 g/cm2 were hermetically sealed in a polyethylene
envelopes in order to avoid radioxenon loss and prevent
water absorption (NaI is hydroscopic). The pellets
thicknesses were determined by weight and area
measurements. The stack of 25 sealed pellets were used.

x4freetext: Thin-target yield.
A stacked foil target /thin
circular foils 10 mm in diam. with thickness which
varied from 0.15-0.20 mg/cm2 was constructed using
enriched metallic lead.
The isotopic composition of the Pb-206 foil-
Each stack consisted of 3 foils /triad/ with three
different Pb isotopes-Pb-206,Pb-207 and Pb-208. A total
of 20 triad /60 Foils with total mass 11 g/cm2 were
used.
- By Compiler - Stack construction does not exclude
influence of recoil nuclei lost on measured cross
section.
